Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize here as the fourth US president in history.
Among other things, he will receive a diploma, a medal and a check for 1.4 million dollars for his exceptional efforts to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The head of the White House will arrive in the Norwegian capital in the morning with his wife Michelle and will be busy.
First, he will visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with five members of the committee that selected him in October from among 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple is then scheduled to meet with Norway&#39;s King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will receive it as the fourth US president, but only the third, to receive the award directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will speak about the Afghan war when accepting the award.
The president does not want to shy away from the topic, realizing that he is accepting the award as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
He increased the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, a fact that none of his critics will fail to point out.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to give them to charity, but has not yet decided on a specific charity.
The packed program will then take the president and his wife to a banquet where, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, there will also be the prime minister and 250 other invited guests.
From the beginning, Obama was more reserved about the award.
For example, he stated that he felt that he did not fully deserve her.
He also repeated several times that this award is not just for him, but for everyone who strives for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he said that it was a &quot;call to action&quot; for him.
