USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is almost comical with what schoolboy effort Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered the stupidest, on the Afghan question.
When he finally sweated out his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he copied it over the copier from Bush&#39;s Iraq script three years earlier.
Not only does he use the phrase &quot;as in Iraq&quot; several times in the text itself, but he did not even hesitate to use the title of Bush&#39;s statement from January 2007 as the title of his own declaration: &quot;A New Way Forward&quot;.
At the same time, three years ago he himself criticized Bush&#39;s idea to send fresh military reinforcements to Iraq, plagued by civil war, as &quot;an irresponsible and, in its consequences, catastrophic decision.&quot;
However, the following months showed that Bush&#39;s strategy, based on the recommendations of field commanders, was the only one possible and so successful that Iraq is not even mentioned in the news today.
It did not improve Bush&#39;s reputation, but it objectively left his successor with a much more grateful starting situation than might have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama is hoping for a miracle to happen again.
Field commanders again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House, despite subordination customs.
He asked for 40 thousand men so that he could break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but couldn&#39;t think of anything better, so at least he cheated the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to squeeze the promise of another 5,000 from Europe, even though he originally expected at least 10.
The most problematic aspect of Obama&#39;s entire strategy seems to be his intention to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in as little as 18 months and complete the process within three years. The entire Obama doctrine raises more questions than it answers.
Many doubt that the half-hearted increase will bear the same fruit as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well-ordered, its leaders honor agreements.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the opposite symptom - no one can be trusted and no agreements are kept.
Under these conditions, the Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing masters every day, are ill-prepared.
Political institutions, even if they are formally established, will remain only a Potemkin village, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult due to the opacity of the situation, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even building an &quot;actionable state&quot;, which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation, does not seem very realistic.
The time horizon of Obama&#39;s strategy is striking in its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of exploding.
Only a truly romantic soul, untouched by reality, can believe that soldiers sent into the tumult of war in order to &quot;return home soon&quot; will cause the miracle performed here.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will perceive it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is on the decline.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically affecting the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the difficult question for the United States will be whether to try to solve the problem with military force.
It will be necessary to answer it just at the time when, according to Obama, America will begin a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also mean a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only band-aid for Barack Obama is the fact that the presidential election is three years away, leaving plenty of time to come up with another strategy if this one turns out to be a total flop.
Goldman Sachs executives will no longer receive cash bonuses
Senior executives at Goldman Sachs will not receive cash bonuses this year.
