I told him, &#39;If I&#39;m going to play you, I&#39;m going to have to have access to you.
The 72-year-old actor, who won an award for his role in Eastwood&#39;s box-office drama Million Dollar Baby, has already played, for example, an abolitionist-turned-slave leader, a fictional US president and even a god in Evan the Divine, but rarely someone who is still alive and as important to many people as Mandela.
The former South African statesman was in prison for 27 years for his active work to end apartheid in South Africa.
He was released in 1990 and then became the country&#39;s president for four years.
In 1993, he was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
Invictus is the Latin word for unconquered and is the title of a poem by the English author William Ernest Henley published in 1875.
The challenge was to speak like him
The film is the true story of how Nelson Mandela joined forces with South African rugby team captain Francois Pienaar to help unite the country. President-elect Mandela knows that his nation remains racially and economically divided after apartheid.
He believes that he can unite his people through sport, so he decides to unite the rugby players who are among the outsiders on a global scale.
The South African team would eventually advance to the 1995 World Cup.
Freeman worked for several years to bring Mandela&#39;s story to the screen.
I had no other goal than to play this role as close to reality as possible, said Freeman.
The biggest challenge, of course, was to speak like him.
The actor said that if he and the world politician were from the same area, he would try to meet Mandela, have dinner with him, be backstage before his speech.
Most importantly, he wanted to shake Mandela&#39;s hand.
I found that when I shake your hand, I take your energy, it transfers, and I felt like I knew how you felt, he said.
It is important for me to try to become a different person.
In the film, Matt Damon portrays François Pienaar, the captain of the predominantly white national rugby team.
The actor said he had six months to prepare for the role in the tough world of rugby.
The big surprise for him in the end was when he met Pienaar for the first time at his house.
I remember ringing the doorbell, he opened the door, and the first thing I said to François Pienaar in my life was: &#39;I look much bigger in the movie&#39;.
Despite the stark differences in the actors&#39; characters compared to their real-life counterparts, under director Eastwood&#39;s direction, Invictus: The Undefeated has received positive reviews and is rumored to be Oscar-winning.
Daily Variety film critic Todd McCarthy summed up his assessment in the words: &quot;It was a very good story, a very well-made film.&quot;
