In Russian newspapers, &quot;Bulava&quot; is already being described as a &quot;rocket that doesn&#39;t fly&quot;.
A rocket that doesn&#39;t fly but lights up
This was already the 13th attempt in a row and initially proceeded normally.
Only at the end of the flight did technical damage to the apparatus occur again.
Apparently the engine in the third stage of the rocket exploded.
This time, &quot;Bulava&quot; was launched from the nuclear submarine Dmitry Donsky, which was sailing under the surface of the White Sea.
This type of missile allows firing from a vessel that is in motion and submerged at the same time.
Therefore, it is likely that the mysterious light over Norway, caused by an unspecified flying object, was indeed a malfunctioning &quot;Bulava&quot;.
After all, the Norwegians had no doubt from the first moment that it was a Russian missile.
