Czech discovery: a substance that also affects &#39;hardened&#39; HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow down the spread of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already acquired immunity against drugs.
In some cases, this fact outweighs the fact that the compound does not act as strongly on the common variant of the virus as some already available drugs.
AIDS cannot be cured yet.
However, a combination of drugs that prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body can significantly prolong the lives of patients.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus multiplication also results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from VŠCHT Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They showed that substances called metallocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metallocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all drugs used today, and therefore may overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new &#39;improved&#39; compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metallocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages made of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are linked by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease-induced cleavage of the HIV virus, mature infectious virus particles would not be produced.
When we stop the HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient&#39;s body, the scientists explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In the work published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is further systematically modified.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in a test tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from patients infected with the HIV virus.
The effect of metallocarboranes on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as with clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and also their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modifications make metallocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at the design of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Structural Biology Laboratory at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
