New vaccination
Free vaccines for August children
From January, children born on or after August 2 last year can be vaccinated against pneumococci free of charge.
The condition is that they have not yet received a single dose of vaccination.
Those who started vaccinating last year or earlier must pay for the next revaccination themselves.
The first dose of vaccination must be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child&#39;s age.
Already last year, a quarter of families voluntarily had their children vaccinated against pneumococci.
At the same time, parents paid 1,600 crowns for one dose or more.
When vaccinating the youngest children, four doses are needed.
In total, experts estimate that health insurance companies spend 300 to 450 thousand crowns per year on vaccinations.
But it will save on the treatment that children without vaccination would need.
Up until now, the state has paid roughly 500,000 per year for all general vaccinations of children.
Paid vaccination was introduced by the so-called Janot package.
Pneumococcus causes otitis media, but also serious infections including meningitis and blood poisoning.
According to hospital surveys, up to 28 children under 10 years of age will die from pneumococcal infections in our country.
In addition to the Czech Republic, they have introduced paid universal vaccination of children against pneumococci in approximately 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, there are opinions that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
From January, it should be covered by insurance companies and optional.
For example, the head of the civic association Nahlas, Rudolf Kalovský, indicated that compulsory vaccination would be better.
His association has been promoting pneumococcal vaccines for a long time.
The experts at the international conference that our association participated in were not entirely satisfied with the fact that we have voluntary vaccination.
It&#39;s not exactly ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that at least this was achieved.
I think this is the path we have to take now, said Kalovský.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination procedure.
At the moment we are not thinking about it at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Professional Society of Pediatric Practitioners, acknowledges that voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all children were vaccinated, it could be considered to reduce the number of revaccinations.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of new parents to have their infants vaccinated against pneumococci starting next year.
Vaccination against pneumococci is also groundbreaking in that, as the first general vaccination of children, it is covered by health insurance companies, not the state.
Insurance companies should spend money on prevention, thereby saving on further treatment, explains Cabrnochová.
Doctors will have to buy the drugs themselves
But related to this are the worries of practicing pediatricians, which are related to purchasing vaccines.
According to the original plan, the vaccines were to be purchased by insurance companies and doctors would receive them in the same way as the state supplies them with substances for other vaccinations.
However, some MPs feared that insurance companies could &quot;take money out of health insurance&quot; in this way.
Therefore, doctors will have to buy the substances and wait for the insurance companies to reimburse them.
According to estimates, individual pediatricians will invest 40 thousand per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It won&#39;t be easy at all, says Cabrnochová.
