In an aging China, changing course
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters that read &quot;Mother Earth is too exhausted to support more children&quot; and &quot;One more child means one more grave&quot;.
Then they learned the lesson that when official government posts in Shanghai, alarmed by their city&#39;s low birthrate and aging population, suddenly reversed course this summer and began encouraging young couples, their response was immediate and determined: Never.
We have always devoted all our time and energy to just one child.
We left nothing for others, says Wang, 31, a human resources manager who has an 8-month-old son.
China&#39;s more than 30-year-old one-child policy has been implemented, creating two generations of only notoriously chubby and spoiled children, affectionately nicknamed &quot;little emperors,&quot; and the country is threatened by a population crisis.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple, compared with six before the policy took effect, according to UN data.
A breakdown of the population, where the number of people aged 60 and over is predicted to skyrocket from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050. That&#39;s well above the overall average of around 20 percent.
The imbalance is greater in wealthy coastal cities with university-educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over made up nearly 22 percent of Shanghai&#39;s registered population, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai Municipal Commission for Population and Family Planning, said many couples must have children to &quot;help reduce the proportion of the aging population and the shrinking workforce in the future&quot;.
He says it&#39;s about &quot;being old doesn&#39;t mean being rich -- like in developed countries like Japan or Sweden&quot;.
Gradual calming down
Enshrined in the country&#39;s constitution in 1978, China&#39;s one-child policy is arguably the most controversial mandate introduced under Communist Party rule to this day.
Couples who violated the policy faced hefty fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some areas -- and job discrimination.
Chinese officials have pushed for policies that have helped the country prevent critical depletion of natural resources, while human rights advocates have been condemned for pushing the policy.
In rural areas, some officials forced pregnant women to have second-child abortions.
Additionally, many couples had to undergo sexist selective abortions, leading to an unnaturally high ratio of males to females.
In past years, population officials have gradually softened their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they generally allowed a number of exceptions -- including urban dwellers, members of national minorities and cases where a man and a woman were only children -- and in 2007 they softened the diction of their hardline slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Peking University&#39;s Institute of Population Research, said central government officials had previously debated more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one partner was an only child.
In June, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost overnight, posters urging parents to have only one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing how it would be permissible to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples at their homes and slip flyers under their doors.
They also promised to provide emotional and financial counseling for those who choose to have more than one child.
The response has been chilly, family planning officials said.
