They want to provide the best for the first child, he stated.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would like to have two children and were legally allowed to.
But like many Chinese who only have inadequate health and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social safety net, the choice could be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge the one-child policy as a contentious legal issue, says Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with their first child.
Yes, we were deprived of the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not just politics.
It&#39;s about money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for hesitation.
Wang, a human resources manager, says they only want one child because she, too, was an only child: &quot;We were the center of attention in our families and everyone took care of us.
We weren&#39;t used to providing care and didn&#39;t really want to care for others.
Chen Zijian, 42, who owns a translation company, put it more bluntly.
For middle-class, two-career parents who have reduced birth rates, he said, being successful means being selfish.
