UN group outlines plan to cut emissions.
The U.N.-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by largely unruly attitudes and finger-pointing -- focused again on Friday on releasing a document that proposes ambitious cuts in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations bearing most of the burden in the near future.
The text, which may provide a starting point for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, highlights remaining obstacles as well as illuminating a way forward.
But important progress was seen in the ill-timed talks with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Created by a UN ad hoc working group, the text subtly outlines how much money rich countries should give poor ones to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And it provides a range of choices on key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies to limit their carbon output and what should be the upper limit of global temperature increase that policymakers will still be able to tolerate.
That adds a lot of flexibility to the process, says John Coequyt, senior director of the Sierra Club of Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, condenses 180 pages of text from the talks to focus on what the UN&#39;s top climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as the &quot;big picture&quot;.
It outlines a possible deal in which industrialized nations could collectively cut their emissions to 25 to 45 percent below 1990 levels within a year, while major developing countries could cut their emissions to 15 to 30 percent over that period.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions by 2050 between 50 and 95 percent.
The European Union negotiated a fast-track Friday pledge to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries embrace climate change adaptation -- from managing floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
But Friday still unleashed the same kind of verbal fireworks that dominated the talks last week.
US special climate envoy Todd Stern rejected the speech, calling for binding greenhouse gas emissions reductions for industrialized countries versus voluntary ones for major emerging economies if they were not funded by the developed world.
The move signaled that the Obama administration has taken a tougher line toward China than Bush administration officials took just two years ago.
The United States will not accede to the treaty without the transfer of major developing countries and implementation of actions, said Stern, who also complained that the text was not sufficient to secure the restrictions and should be vetted by outside observers.
Stern made the comments an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei told the U.S. chief climate negotiator that either a lack of &quot;common sense&quot; or &quot;extraordinary irresponsibility&quot; led him to say earlier in the week that the United States would not financially help China to could deal with global warming.
With the future of the economic trajectory of the world&#39;s major powers at stake, tussles have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is mostly about preserving individual economies rather than preserving the planet, between China and the United States over meeting their respective commitments, while poorer nations point out that two dozen of the world&#39;s most powerful countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take stronger action.
Ricardo Ulate, Costa Rica&#39;s delegate, said it&#39;s not surprising that major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of curbing greenhouse gases, while vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in finding ways to hold big emitters accountable for their actions.
It&#39;s clearly a play that a new economic hegemony is developing, said Ulate, who also serves as a regional adviser on regional climate change in Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the effects of climate change have indicated they would like to continue pushing for a legally binding agreement in Copenhagen, but most of the main participants said the best outcome of the talks would be a political agreement.
The 43-member alliance of small island states produced a 24-page draft agreement last Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who led international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said the small island nation&#39;s push &quot;has put political pressure on the whole political process&quot; in part because they are now united in demanding action from growing economies such as China and India.
The talks took on new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the remaining contentious issues before the heads of government vie for a deal.
High-ranking officials, such as India&#39;s environment minister Jairam Ramesh and China&#39;s deputy minister, stepped off planes and walked through the halls of the Bella Center to closed-door meetings and new conferences so they could lay out the claims to be considered next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering - with 13,000 people moving daily behind the convention center, guitar-playing activists staging ironic spectacles at night about the countries they believed had sent them, and proposals being passed from hand to hand on paper rather than electronically by mail -- controlled by challenge.
The intensity is only a superstructure: almost all key ministers were present in Copenhagen, and earlier on Wednesday 60 heads of state.
We got into the high categories, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, said Assistant Secretary for Global Policy at International Conservation.
The heavyweights are coming.
