The UDF association is raising its voice and calling on the Nouveau Center party to stop using their acronym.
The UDF association, controlled by MoDem François Bayrou&#39;s party, responded on Friday to Nouveau Center president Hervé Morin&#39;s attempt to appropriate the acronym of Giscard&#39;s former party, saying it must not use the acronym in any media under threat of criminal prosecution.
Hervé Morin has publicly announced his intention to appropriate the UDF acronym, saying that François Bayrou does not deserve to carry its legacy after shaking hands with the left.
The Minister of Defense, whose party is a partner of the UMP, had planned to confirm this strategy before the National Council of the Nouveau Center (NC) movement on Saturday.
This move of his received the support of the deputy Hervé de Charette (former pro-UMP now pro-NC), who claims ownership of the UDF brand because he was the first to have it registered in 2004 with the National Institute of Industrial Property (l&#39;Institut national de la propriété industrielle ).
But on Friday night, a committee of the UDF Association run by friends of François Bayrou, who have no intention of being expropriated, broke their silence and made a formal request to both the minister and the MP to stop using the acronym and hand over ownership of the trademark, under threat of prosecution.
In recent days, you have raised alarming statements that you will propose to your political movement to +retake+ the acronym UDF, writes the Association in its letter signed by 19 of the 24 committee members, including François Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez from the MoDem party and Senator Jean Arthuis from Alliance centriste.
At the same time, you considered it appropriate to place on your promotional materials and on the welcome website of your movement the name +Nouveau center+, with the slogan +UDF dneška+, the signatories of the letter also state.
As you know, you have no right to use this acronym, explains the UDF committee, which asks the NC movement to &quot;immediately remove all mentions of the UDF name from all promotional materials including (its) website&quot;.
At the same time, he asks Hervé de Charette &quot;to transfer the ownership of the trademark to the legitimate owners&quot;.
If you do not do so, we will approach the courts so that the law and the legitimate rights of UDF members are respected, the signatories warn.
In their letter, they state that the UDF &quot;has been a full-fledged political movement since 1978&quot; and recall that Mr. Morin and his friends &quot;chose to leave in 2007&quot; to create a rival movement, just as others did in 2002 to found the UMP.
According to them, the Nouveau center movement therefore has no right to use the abbreviation UDF (Union pour la démocratie française).
At the same time, they recall that the last UDF congress voted in 2007 to join MoDem for three years and to create a committee charged with defending the &quot;moral and material interests&quot; of the association founded by Valéry Giscard d&#39;Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, the committee continues, &quot;when he registered the trademark&quot;, he was not &quot;a member of the UDF for three years&quot;, but of the UMP.
He scandalously and fraudulently used the non-existent registration of the acronym to do so on his own account.
This tactlessness is beginning to turn into a crime, they declare, before commenting with irony on NC&#39;s strategy: &quot;It seems to us that both in politics and in everyday life it is more valuable to make a name for oneself than to emerge from anonymity by fraudulent acceptance names to which we have no right&quot;.
The case of Liliane Bettencourt : François-Marie Banier will be tried for abusing a state of weakness.
The court in Nanterre decided on Friday to try the artist François-Marie Banier and give a verdict on whether he took advantage of the frailty of the 80-year-old billionaire to deprive her of part of her fortune, which her daughter Liliane Bettencourt accuses him of.
The photographer (age 62), known for his celebrity photos, will be tried on April 15 and 16, 2010 for abuse of a state of infirmity, a crime punishable by a maximum sentence of 3 years and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision confirms that there will indeed be a trial in what can be described as a family saga of one of the richest families in France, in which a mother and daughter are fighting each other and fighting for the management of the cosmetics empire L&#39;Oréal.
However, the 15th Criminal Court also ordered a medical examination of 87-year-old Liliana Bettencourt, which should be carried out by a panel of three doctors.
The heiress and major shareholder of L&#39;Oréal has always refused to undergo such an examination, certainly not under the conditions offered by the prosecutor&#39;s office in Nanterre during the investigation.
The doctors who will be elected on Friday should prepare a report by March 10, 2010 and at the same time give a statement on whether Liliana Bettencourt could have been in a state of weakness and for what period.
I think he will undergo it.
I will talk to her about the matter, Ms. Bettencourt&#39;s lawyer, Georges Kiejman, said after the hearing.
As for Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers&#39; lawyer, Olivier Metzner, he welcomed the court&#39;s decision.
It is excellent news(...). Expertise will show that this old lady in need of protection was manipulated by (M. Banier), he confirmed.
It has been two years since Liliana Bettencourt&#39;s only daughter launched criminal proceedings against François-Marie Banier, a photographer and jack-of-all-trades, whom she accuses of taking advantage of her mother&#39;s frailty for years to obtain a billion-euro gift in the form of checks, life insurance contracts or master paintings .
On the other hand, Liliane Bettencourt has always refused to be manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers a long-time friend.
While the court had to consider the validity of the lawsuit filed by Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers&#39; court speech on Friday turned into a family truth hour at times.
Liliana Bettencourt&#39;s lawyer presented three letters that his client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) sent to her notary, in which she expressed her distrust of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers&#39; husband.
In a 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the attorney, &quot;could you please explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once or twice a day for fifteen years.
I have never been able to speak to Françoise since she got married&quot;.
The public prosecutor&#39;s office in Nanterre found again that the action of the complainant was not justified, all the more so because the guardianship judge recently rejected her request to start proceedings to issue legal protection for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt &quot;is fully capable of attending court, she is not under protection or guardianship.
No one else will act for her&quot;, confirmed the representative of the prosecutor&#39;s office, Marie-Christine Daubigneyová.
Ultimately, the court decided to rule on Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers&#39; eligibility at the time of the trial.
Managerial revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle to develop economic intelligence has been pointless…
For more than a decade, the behavior of management of large companies towards employees has resembled the approach of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about getting employees to identify with &quot;values&quot; determined from above, as it was before, when it was necessary to impose products that arose on the consumer from the ideas of the heads of factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of entrepreneurial companies, the marketing revolution has aligned market-conquering strategies in the right direction...although authoritarian efforts to impose products that differ from customer preferences regularly return!
A passive attitude of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
The suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only a visible part of a much more widespread general phenomenon that mainly affects managerial staff.
This demobilization adversely affects the development of all intellectual functions of society, including research and development, and more importantly, economic intelligence.
And indeed, EI &quot;requires from all parties involved (...) an active approach and the ability to anticipate&quot; and demands from employees commitments that are completely at odds with the income of authoritarian management.
That is why we are calling for a management revolution, which should aim to put workers at the center of interest of the company as well as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal polls.
Will internal opinion polls - such as a questionnaire submitted to Orange employees - contribute to a revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I&#39;m afraid not.
Mainly because I have already convinced myself that when faced with a new situation, the structure after various detours will preferably return to what it has always done!
Furthermore, because authoritarianism, as one of the pathologies of power, increases in proportion to the severity of one&#39;s own failures.
And finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Because they are graduates of engineering colleges, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
For the sake of intellectual convenience, they adopt the old behaviorist theory, currently revived by &quot;neuroscientists&quot; from the USA and widely disseminated without much knowledge by scientific institutes and the media.
With the fact that it is possible to move the &quot;levers&quot; (sic) of the involvement of managers, a recent survey by the Ipsos agency on the Figaro.fr website showed that it only confirms managers in their position of mechanical management, unsuitable for today&#39;s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors.
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes the adoption of a final vision of human behavior.
It consists in incorporating a basic insight into all management intentions and practices: For employees, commitments to the company will only be possible if they appear as a clear means of achieving their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Currently, this concept of employee motivation is only dealt with by Motivational Functional Analysis studies.
These studies have shown that they evaluate their businesses on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them to evaluate, through the image that speaks of the business, what it offers them to realize their life goals.
By identifying and measuring these mobilization factors, managers can control, predict and anticipate their &quot;social performance&quot; and put their human resource management &quot;on the right track&quot;.
This creates a fertile ground for the development of solid and effective economic intelligence.
The Oslo speech: &quot;just war&quot; earned Obama praise from the right.
The American right on Friday welcomed Barack Obama&#39;s speech in Oslo the day before, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner defended the concept of a &quot;just war&quot; against the United States&#39; enemies.
Conservatives who initially mocked Obama&#39;s Oct. 9 award this time applauded the president&#39;s speech, including Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, Palin, the muse of the Republican right wing, told USA Today, adding that she herself had addressed the &quot;sometimes necessary&quot; theme of war in her forthcoming memoir.
Of course, war is the last thing Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
All terrorists should be detained there, he believes.
President Obama, who inherited two wars in Afghanistan and Iraq from his predecessor George W. Bush, justified the troop deployment in Oslo on Thursday, using a speech to explain his decision to send 30,000 more troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another Obama opponent, Newt Gingrich, assessed that the president did a &quot;very good job&quot; in Oslo.
I think that the speech was really very good, congratulated the former chairman of the House of Representatives, who especially appreciated the president&#39;s mention of &quot;the existence of evil in the world&quot;.
In a way, I considered this speech quite historic, Gingrich said during an interview on the radio show &quot;The Takeaway&quot;.
The former lawmaker, considered by some to be a possible Republican candidate in the 2012 presidential election, was excited to see a &quot;left-wing president&quot; remind members of the Nobel Prize committee &quot;that they themselves would not be free and could not present the peace prize if the use of force did not exist&quot;.
According to Michael Gerson, former George W. Bush speechwriter and now Washington Post editor, Obama gave &quot;a very American speech.&quot;
Not only did he present himself as a &quot;global citizen&quot; as always, but he &quot;spoke like an American president&quot; and reminded Europeans &quot;that they live in a safe bubble that they did not create and that they are not doing much to preserve it,&quot; Gerson assessed.
Among the few right-wing dissidents is Bush-era hawk, former UN ambassador John Bolton, who called the speech &quot;monotonous, bloated and uninspired,&quot; according to the National Review Online website.
To the president&#39;s left, Democratic Rep. Dennis Kucinich, for example, is horrified to see Barack Obama justify the use of force.
&quot;When we wrap war in the mantle of justice, we can easily justify the massacre of innocent people,&quot; he warned.
However, the center-left press takes a favorable view of the president.
Although the Los Angeles Times continues to consider the awarding of the Peace Prize to Obama premature, it assessed his performance as an &quot;overperformance&quot; even for a speaker known for his talent.
The speech from Oslo should serve as a guide to international decisions in conflict resolution, in the fight against poverty and oppression&quot;, states the Californian newspaper enthusiastically.
Obama &quot;delivered a speech as needed&quot;, evaluated the New York Times, calling the speech &quot;simple and instructive&quot;.
Road hauliers: three marathons for deal to save Christmas supply.
After three marathon negotiations, road transport unions and the TLF, the only employers&#39; organization left to the end, reached an agreement on Friday evening that ended a call for strike action and the threat that hung over the delivery of Christmas supplies.
The Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, expressed his &quot;joy&quot; at the signing of the agreement on Friday, after several negotiations that began on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, negotiators broke up early Friday morning with the hope that the text of the agreement would be signed as soon as possible by late morning.
And this despite the fact that three employers&#39; organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) withdrew from the negotiations.
But it took another more than six hours of the meeting, which started at 11 am, for everyone to agree and at 6 pm to sign the agreement.
The conflict &quot;would be very damaging to businesses&quot; and &quot;there would be a risk of disrupting the year-end holidays,&quot; Bussereau said.
The wording of the text includes a wage increase of 4% for the lowest salaries (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest salaries (international transport).
The hourly wage for the lowest salaries increases from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It&#39;s not much, but there&#39;s a lot of effort behind it, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
Tonight we will give orders to our members that there will be no blockades, no blockades of supply centers.
But there may still be a few naysayers who are not satisfied,&quot; he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of the TLF, welcomed &quot;the right agreement&quot;, although it was difficult to admit the high salary increases given the international competition&quot;.
According to him, there will be an increase of 170 euros per month for the lowest wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It is an agreement of common sense and respect for employees, declared CMaxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed the &quot;historic agreement&quot;.
According to Richard Jaubert (CGT), this is an &quot;acceptable compromise&quot;.
The agreement also envisages a 3% revaluation of travel expenses and a report on the state of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will also allow focusing on the issue of the 13th salary and the modernization of the collective agreement.
Bussereau recalled the &quot;100 million euro reduction in corporate payroll taxes&quot; that was the subject of the government&#39;s amendment to the 2009 budget bill, which was voted on by the National Assembly on the night of Thursday to Friday.
The government will ask the Senate for a &quot;unanimous&quot; vote.
The signature allows that this agreement will apply first to companies that are members of this organization, and later to the entire field, in case of expansion by the Ministry of Labour.
It will take place &quot;as soon as possible&quot;, assured Bussereau.
Only the disapproval of employers&#39; organizations can slow down the whole process.
The FNTR organization talks about a &quot;bad deal&quot; because 100 million euros &quot;was already offered to the sector as part of the carbon tax compensation&quot;.
The Secretary of State for Transportation forced us into an emergency meeting not as a result of mutual analysis, but to avoid angering turkey eaters in the run-up to the Christmas holidays, Unostra complained.
For the Otre organization, there is a risk that the agreement will &quot;bury a large number of small and medium-sized enterprises from the sector&quot; in the next 12 months.
RER A suburban trains: disruption of services at the weekend, unions unhappy with the proposals of the transport company RATP.
Service disruptions on the RER A commuter train line, France&#39;s largest urban public transport line, will continue into the weekend as talks between unions and RATP management on Friday failed to produce any concrete results on the bonus claim on the second day of the strike.
On Saturday and Sunday, the days of the important shopping weekend before Christmas, trains will run only between 10am and 8pm, on the main section (between La Défence and Nation) every second train will run, outside this section only one train in four.
The connection with SNCF will be interrupted in Nanterre Préfecture and passengers will be forced to transfer to another train.
The Galeries Lafayette department stores, which expect over 200,000 customers every day, welcomed the fact that &quot;RATP tried to secure connections with large department stores&quot;.
The RER A line runs from the west to the east of the Paris agglomeration.
The RATP-managed section runs from Saint-Germain-en-Laye and Nanterre to Boissy-Saint-Léger and Marne-La-Vallée.
On Friday, one train out of two was running during peak hours, and virtually no trains ran during off-peak hours as planned.
As on Thursday, the residents of Ile de France arranged themselves differently and there was no confusion on the platforms.
So early in the morning there were far fewer people than usual at the Saint-Germain-en-Laye (Yvelines) station, partly because pupils and students were absent.
Jack Nbakina, an engineer, 29 years old from Boissy-Saint-Léger (Val-de-Marne) explained that he got up &quot;an hour and a half early to make sure he would arrive on time&quot;.
The Saint-Lazare station was not overcrowded, state railway SNCF said, as a larger number of ushers and security guards had been expected.
RER A commuter trains operated by SNCF in the direction from or to Cergy-Le-Haut arrived or departed from Saint-Lazare station with a metro connection.
Further general meetings of the strikers will be held on Saturday and Sunday to assess the results of Friday afternoon&#39;s management meeting, which the union described as &quot;weak&quot;.
The RER management proposes negotiations on a special protocol for RER A suburban trains in all respects, adjustment of working hours, career progression, etc.
However, this is not the point for drivers who demand a well-deserved premium, according to Thierry Garon (Unions South).
The RATP has even shelved proposals on the bonus for the time being, angering the CGT, who said management &quot;was unable to resolve the issue while the tour operators and the SNCF were able to&quot;.
At the new meeting, which is scheduled for Monday, &quot;the conditions of the performance of the profession will be reviewed more closely&quot;, specified the transport companies RATP.
Which was the reason why the trade unionists think that the company is &quot;making fun of the weekend passengers&quot;.
In the morning, about 150 drivers occupied the works committee at its Paris headquarters.
The management, which until now had refused any discussion during the strike, therefore decided to hold a meeting in order to &quot;calm things down&quot;.
There is a danger that the conflict will spread to the RER B line on Tuesday, after Unsa and Nezavislí announce a strike alert.
The unions are asking for a bonus worth from 120 (Unsa) to 150 euros, of which 30 euros are variable (CGT, FO, CFDT, Sud (South), Indépendants (Independent)) and complain about the deteriorating working conditions on this line, which daily transports a million passengers.
RER commuter train drivers earn between 2,200 and 2,700 euros in gross wages and 600 to 650 euros in bonuses for irregular working hours and for working on Sundays and holidays in the advanced stages of their careers.
The Turkish judiciary has disbanded for the Kurdish side, and this decision carries heavy consequences.
Turkey&#39;s Constitutional Court ruled on Friday to dissolve the country&#39;s main pro-Kurdish party. This decision immediately sparked protests and demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
The decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which is trying to extend a friendly hand to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become &quot;a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity,&quot; Supreme Court President Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority-seven vote needed to dissolve the party, Kiliç said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysela Tugluk, have been banned from political life for five years.
At the same time, the judge announced the cancellation of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluková and the confiscation of the party&#39;s assets by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP party has 21 seats (out of 500) in Parliament.
The party leadership warned even before the verdict that the MPs would rather leave the Parliament than work in it as MPs without a political affiliation.
The decision is a continuation of a trial started in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation, Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses the DTP of obeying the &quot;orders&quot; of the Kurdistan Workers&#39; Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is a legal political showcase for PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has no &quot;core connection&quot; with the PKK, but refuses to label it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court&#39;s verdict comes as the government extends a friendly hand to the Kurdish community, offering a series of measures to strengthen their rights and attempt to curb Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
The DTP leadership confirmed that the party&#39;s dissolution could lead to renewed tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where many demonstrations against the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan is being held have degenerated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
Since the justice&#39;s decision was announced, thousands of protesters have gathered outside the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast that is populated mostly by Kurds.
Police used tear gas and water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails or threw stones from slingshots.
About a hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said the justice&#39;s decision would only &quot;deepen the despair&quot;.
Turkey cannot solve this issue (of the Kurds, editor&#39;s note) by banning the party, he declared in the press.
The government, formed by a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also condemned the decision.
We are against party interference as a matter of principle.
It doesn&#39;t solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
Political scientist Ahmet Insel commented that this decision is a complete blow to the democratic proposals launched by the government.
Of course, we can expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for one of the deadliest attacks in northern Turkey, which killed seven soldiers three days earlier.
Snow may come
Nicely crisp winter, that&#39;s what Wolfgang Brauburger wants.
Not because he wants to bully citizens, says the head of the FES winter technical services department.
But so that his employees could test and learn how to control all the vehicle technology.
According to meteorologists, this could happen for the first time this weekend.
Over 300 employees and 120 vehicles are ready to take care of the snow and ice.
At the same time, FES is proceeding according to a precise plan.
As soon as it snows all over Frankfurt and the temperatures drop below zero, they will go out on the 20 so-called A sections of the large spreader, explains Brauburger.
These sections include main and thoroughfares such as Neue Weg and Hanauer Landstraße.
But also arrivals for the fire brigade, suburban public transport lines, pedestrian zones and downhill sections such as Atzelbergstraße.
The FES service starts at three in the morning.
If necessary, something like 1,040 kilometers must be sprinkled with moist salt, which holds better, within a maximum of three hours.
That&#39;s why FES starts at three o&#39;clock in the morning &quot;so that the roads are clear when the traffic to work starts&quot;.
It&#39;s not easy when it only starts snowing at 7:30.
Then we have a problem, says the head of the winter technical services department, &quot;because no one is willing to make room for the spreaders&quot;.
Only when it doesn&#39;t snow so much are the access roads and connecting roads, which also include the Rat-Beil-Straße.
Side and side roads have the last priority.
Brauburger knows there will be complaints.
At five o&#39;clock in the morning, FES infantrymen will set off, priority is being given to clearing dangerous places and crossings.
FES usually cannot take care of all cycle paths.
In Frankfurt, there is a special service that monitors especially bridges from 10 p.m. to 4:30 a.m., says Brauburger.
Since ice forms quickly on them, the spreader comes out immediately as soon as the temperature drops below two degrees.
The police will also call them if necessary.
Cradle of the Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-meter-long, 1.50-meter-tall animal ran on two powerful hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short forelimbs with sickle-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have been anything extraordinary.
But Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues write in Thursday&#39;s issue of the journal Science that Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then located in the equatorial dry region of the supercontinent Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window on early dinosaur evolution, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the relationships, distribution and characteristics of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavations at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unheard of for Triassic deposits, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, they collected remains from a total of five individuals.
The discovery confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name &quot;Tawa&quot; comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual find: &quot;Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are very rare, usually only single fragments are found.&quot;
Other dinosaur experts do not share this unqualified enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly sensational, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander from the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared around 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are not complete, which is why the assignment of proto-dinosaurs is mostly questionable.
For example, experts debate when lizards split into three major evolutionary lineages: the carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor, and birds, the &quot;long-necked&quot; four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the herbivorous Ornithischia (bird-eaters), which included for example the Triceratops and Stegosaurus species.
Tawa hallae is the original therapod, according to Nesbitt and colleagues&#39; analysis.
It exhibits an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air sacs, which are also found in birds, the descendants of theropods.
Thanks to air sacs, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
In Tawa hallae, even the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since a related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light bones, the common ancestor of both groups probably created this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Since the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists deduced that lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three lines of development split early and spread from South America to all the continents, which then formed a single land mass as the supercontinent Pangea.
The fact that the team found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods along with Tawa hallae would also speak for this.
The three cannot come from one common, immigrated ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the scientific study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
One even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His assumption could paint a distorted picture, as South America has preserved very many primitive dinosaur fossils, while they are rarely found on other continents.
