Some see images and hear voices while awake that others cannot see or hear.
The boundaries between imagination and reality merge not only with the mentally ill or those under the influence of drugs.
As long as it happens in sleep, everything is fine.
If we lie with our eyes closed in our dark room, we may surround ourselves with the wildest imaginations and fanciful mirages.
However, anyone who experiences dream states while awake, sees and hears things that others cannot see or hear, is considered in today&#39;s Western world to be a fool or a drug addict, or at least a freak.
However, such images and voices do not only occur in the mentally ill or in drug addiction.
Our imaginations are to blame: The same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels occasionally blur the lines between dream, imagination, and reality.
Dreams, an altered state of consciousness, can occur in various forms, at best we call them visions, at worst delusions.
Although the initiator and effect may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New-Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the shamanic states of delirium, psychosis, and hallucinations can all be traced to similar processes.
Hallucinations or visions occur when the balance of the brain&#39;s neuronal transmitters - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - is disrupted and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusions occur very often in schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over him
The connection between delusion and dream has preoccupied philosophers and physicians since antiquity.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dreaming in the waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychology, noted in 1861 &quot;the great similarity of delirium to dream states&quot;, for Sigmund Freud the dream was even &quot;psychosis, with all the nonsense, illusions, deception of the senses&quot; .
It&#39;s autumn 2001, Henning T. turns into a comic book character.
His body is two-dimensional and garishly colored.
Gravity has no power over him, he floats near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him winged devilish figures with blood-red grimaces, baring teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, fiery boots, throw him against the wall, feel the pain all over his body.
Loud, evil voices threaten from the walls and from the radio.
He can no longer bear the voices that curse and insult him.
Henning T. rips two cables from the stereo, knots them into a loop and fastens it to a hook on the ceiling.
He steps onto one speaker and puts the noose around his neck.
He jumps.
The loop allows.
Learn a lesson, shout the chorus of voices tearing his eardrums, &quot;go to the clinic and get treated!&quot;
Today, Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last 2 years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
They were started on LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective paranoid psychosis, in addition he is manic-depressive, takes medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis, I experienced the worst fear and the deepest doubts, he says.
Ghosts are a terrible reality
About one percent of people will fall ill with schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime, it is the second most frequently treated illness in psychiatric clinics after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers can no longer distinguish between the inner and outer world, they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of size, relational illusions or the illusion of persecution.
Hearing voices is especially widespread - voices that give orders, comment or lead dialogues.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon either.
The disabled person is unable to distinguish important from unimportant, the brain cannot filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream, psychosis opens the floodgates to a flood of thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at the University Clinic in Heidelberg.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he falls into a passive role, becoming, like in a dream, overwhelmed by events and unable to actively shape them.
Schizophrenics therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
Comparison with reality is mostly not possible for them, ghosts are a terrible reality, awakening is impossible.
A once-in-a-lifetime hallucination
Unlike in a dream, says Fuchss, &quot;the sensory and spatial structure of reality that a person perceives in psychosis remains fundamentally preserved.&quot;
Delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, alienation of experience occurs within a real framework.
Scientists are still faced with the puzzle of why exactly our brain makes such projections.
Extraordinary states can cause anyone to lose touch with reality for a short period of time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone develops psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Scientists assume that affected individuals have minimal brain damage.
We believe that there is damage to the brain&#39;s neuronal maturation early in development, for example by a viral illness in the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
However, it remains a mystery how the neuronal system malfunction occurs, which did not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the initiator of psychosis, if there is a disposition for it.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmission system.
When our brain boils
The crazy thing is that psychotronics suffer from their hallucinations, and to get rid of them they swallow expensive medications, others give money for drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten from Lübeck.
Whether we perceive hallucinations as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of attitude.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he interpreted his results in the book &quot;Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf&quot; (The Unreal World in Our Head).
Hallucinations belong to the typical accompanying phenomena of psychoses, but also to surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to psychological disorders such as borderline personality or depression, diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer&#39;s or brain trauma are also often present.
Surprisingly, even the brain of a healthy person hallucinates under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of thought contents that are normally repressed.
They occur when the parts of the brain that process sensory perception are overactive or under-repressed; if our brain freezes or if there is a lack of stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition as can brain damage or psychosis.
But also withdrawal of stimuli, stress, worries about love or other exceptional conditions.
In more recent studies, up to a third of those questioned stated that they had experienced a hallucination at least once in their life.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and goes to the local grammar school.
A completely normal girl actually.
If there weren&#39;t those pictures and voices.
During breaks, she might be approached by a tall man with long, dark hair.
When she answers him, her classmates look at her with surprise - no one but her can see or hear this boy.
This shy girl is considered a tight-lipped dreamer, but Sarah K. doesn&#39;t dream, she knows that.
He is awake, hearing and seeing the boy, just as he hears and sees the girl sitting next to him in the pew.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It&#39;s a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy?, he sometimes asks.
But he knows that this boy and other illusions are not real and he disappears again.
At night, the apparitions are rather daunting
Delusions are often a burden.
As she sits in the classroom, she can&#39;t watch the lesson many times because the teacher in her eyes and ears is introducing a new classmate, while he is explaining mathematical equations to everyone else audibly and visibly on the blackboard.
At night, the apparitions are rather daunting.
As she waits in her dark room for sleep, which comes rarely and too late, she often can&#39;t tell if she&#39;s awake or asleep, if the images she sees, the grimaces, or the girl with bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, arise in front of her open eyes. or with closed eyes.
Leave me alone, he yells at the characters.
She doesn&#39;t tell her parents and friends about it, they would think she&#39;s crazy.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows for sure that she is not crazy.
Illusions are also the art of desperation
If someone is socially isolated or deprived of stimuli, they are more likely to hallucinate, Kasten says.
I believe that the brain then does not have enough work and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she had been calling her dad since she could think on her own was not her own father.
Because the same brain regions that process real sensations and sounds are active in visual and acoustic hallucinations, it is difficult for sufferers like Sarah K. to distinguish between delusions and reality. &quot;Every experience&quot;, says Kasten, &quot;takes place in the brain, reality is also displayed there.
Hallucinations are also images created by the brain, which is why they seem so real.&quot;
Kasten also evaluates night dreams as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from hallucinations in acute psychosis.
Compared to schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to evaluate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
A borderline state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our world focused too much on consciousness, the imaginary experience is mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Psychiatry and Psychotherapy Clinic of the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a difficult, painful disease, but it also brings positives, creativity - mirage is also art from despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard investigated the so-called oneiroid form of experiences, a special form of altered consciousness similar to a dream.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictional dreams that the sufferer believes to be real and cannot even retrospectively distinguish them from the waking state.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and himself, for example by a permanent, complete inability to move, he replaces life-threatening real situations with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline state between dream and hallucination.
Because in reality it is not possible to manage a situation, the worlds will change, but the real situation will be present in the imagination.
An intense form of sense support and sense transfer in some excruciating situation that allows us humans with our own shaping ability to go into unconsciousness in an instant.
Everything is real, even later in memories
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book &quot;Herzwechsel&quot; (Exchange of Heart) as a soul-saving action.
He was 49 years old when, following heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, his consciousness took a journey of several days, his body lying motionless in the intensive care unit.
Claussen immersed himself in the world he created, visited strange times and places: He becomes an old man confined to a bed, in a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility who make intoxicants from blood.
He is kidnapped by a Greek on a motorbike to his homeland, while in a hospital bed he surfs a firn in the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He immerses himself completely in the imaginary plot, everything is real, even later in his memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
A dream is another state, it describes one&#39;s experience.
In contrast to dreams, memories from those mental journeys are still distinctly clear years later and in unimportant details.
Even clearer and more intense than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience shatters the horizon of our other real experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, oneiroid states, psychoses, hallucinations and drug intoxication show how fragile our internal images of external reality are even in the waking state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten, &quot;can lead to a distortion of what we call reality.&quot;
A fact that can also be rewarding.
