75% of working mothers have work-related problems related to motherhood.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study &#39;Fertility and the working career of Spanish women&#39;, carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Women&#39;s Institute.
9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 took part in the study and the results are unequivocal: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities on the labor market due to motherhood.
The study emphasizes that at the beginning of cohabitation, there are many differences in opinions about the number of children, depending on whether they work or not, and also according to the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job start living with a partner earlier, give birth to their first child earlier and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable jobs, especially in the public sector, delay cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
&quot;Women aged 35 to 49 with a stable job have their first child on average 3.7 years after cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 in the case of women who devoted a larger part of their lives to achieving their stable job and therefore had to postpone cohabitation and the arrival of children.
The type of occupation also has a strong effect on motherhood, although it has a smaller effect on the start of cohabitation with a partner&quot;, explains Margarita Delgado, who is engaged in research at CSIC.
Another factor influencing the age of women at the time of marriage and the birth of a child is the level of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35 to 49 years, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 or 32.1.
&quot;There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with primary education get married and give birth to their first child even before finding a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education go the opposite way, preferring to get a stable job, before getting married and having their first child&quot;, says Delgado.
