After the days of wine and roses since last spring, when asset inflation represented the prevailing mood in the markets, uncertainty has resurfaced in the markets, which should not be surprising as it is already a natural state in an environment where executives are making decisions about the future, which itself is unsure of herself.
The remedy used by central banks to stabilize the market was to monetize debt through direct asset purchases and indirectly to release liquidity at a near-zero exchange rate so that financial institutions could purchase assets for deduction.
Central banks have already confirmed that outright asset purchases are virtually over and, without questioning their disjointed liquidity policies, are starting to throw some sand into the wheels, as the Bank of Spain did with its auction last year.
Investors therefore doubt the ability of the global economy to sustain an economic recovery without such unorthodox measures, and we are participating in a return to risk-adverse returns.
Stock market volatility and corporate bond spreads have regained points, although they are still a long way from the abnormal levels they reached at the start of the year.
States were forced to socialize private risk, which again affected public indebtedness.
There is a renewed push for quality and the US, Japan and Germany have become the haven of choice for investors, widening the differentiation of eurozone countries against Germany.
Spain was hardly affected by this instability, but at that time Standard &amp; Poor&#39;s came and threatened a new downgrade review of the Kingdom of Spain.
On the other hand, some uncertainty is not unhelpful in silencing the advocates of moral hazard, who have again sought to burden the consciences of those responsible for world economic policy to curb the devastating effects of credit-to-employment restrictions, when in fact a new Thanksgiving should be declared.
