If, as we expect, we are ahead of a period of normalization of transitory risk premiums, they would be within expectations after some excesses in supported positions.
In the Spanish case, while our public debt differentials will increase just like European corporate bonds, we need not worry.
If European differences narrow and ours continue to widen, it would be a typically Spanish risk.
The Standard &amp; Poor&#39;s thing is just an anecdote. With our leading indicators forcing most study services to anticipate their recovery scenarios and revise their growth scenario for 2011, including the OCDE and the European Commission to return to the Japanese scenario, it does not bode well for the Spanish economy to live up to this warning.
