Spain, on the other hand, is only the third country to receive the most money through the Champions, despite having won the most titles of all (five against four for Italy, three for England and two for Germany).
Distribution
This apparent paradox is explained by the complex procedure used by UEFA to distribute the money.
For this financial year, the body chaired by Michel Platini plans to earn 1.090 million for the Champions League.
Of this money, UEFA allocates 413.1 million for fixed payments: each of the 20 clubs that participated in the preliminary classification round (including Atlético Madrid) received 2.1 million.
in addition, those who achieved participation received 3.8 million just for their presence, in addition to an additional 550,000 euros for each match in which they participate.
There is also a bonus for a win (€800,000) and a draw (€400,000 for each team). Eight finalists will receive three million each; eight quarter-finalists3.3 million.
Each of the last four will receive 4 million.
The champion earns 9 million, while the runner-up earns 5.2 million.
In this way, the club will earn a minimum of 7.1 million and a maximum of 31.2 million on fixed payments.
On the other hand, Barça received 2.5 million for winning the European Super Cup in August.
In addition, there are variable payments for which 337.8 million is intended.
This money is divided according to the relative value of each television market.
The Spanish one is one of the main ones and has four allocated seats.
Last year&#39;s champion will receive 40% of the allocated money, second 30%, third 20% and fourth 10%.
The second part will be paid according to the number of matches that will be played that year.
